'''Jennifer Lynn Lopez'''<ref name=Cartlidge-book /> (born July 24, 1969), also known by her nickname '''J.Lo''', is an American singer, actress, and dancer. In 1991, Lopez began appearing as a [[List of In Living Color cast members#Fly Girls (house dance troupe)|Fly Girl]] dancer on ''[[In Living Color]]'', where she remained a regular until she decided to pursue an acting career in 1993. For her first leading role in the 1997 [[Selena]] [[Selena (film)|biopic of the same name]], Lopez became the first Latin actress to earn over US$1 million for a film. She went on to star in ''[[Anaconda (film)|Anaconda]]'' (1997) and ''[[Out of Sight]]'' (1998), and established herself as the highest-paid Latin actress in Hollywood.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Solid as a Rock|magazine=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|date=July 2003|page=96|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3yYEAAAAMBAJ|accessdate=August 25, 2017}}</ref>

Lopez ventured into the music industry with her debut studio album ''[[On the 6]]'' (1999), which helped propel the [[Latin American music in the United States#1990s Latin Explosion|Latin pop movement]] in American music, and later starred in the psychological horror ''[[The Cell]]'' (2000). With the simultaneous release of her second studio album ''[[J.Lo (album)|J.Lo]]'' and her romantic comedy ''[[The Wedding Planner]]'' in 2001, Lopez became the first woman to have a number-one album and film in the same week. Her 2002 release, ''[[J to tha L–O! The Remixes]]'', became the first remix album in history to debut atop the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]. Later that year, she released her third studio album ''[[This Is Me... Then]]'' and starred in the film ''[[Maid in Manhattan]]''.

After starring in ''[[Gigli]]'' (2003), a critical and commercial failure, Lopez subsequently starred in the successful [[romantic comedy|romantic comedies]] ''[[Shall We Dance? (2004 film)|Shall We Dance?]]'' (2004) and ''[[Monster-in-Law]]'' (2005). Her fifth studio album, ''[[Como Ama una Mujer]]'' (2007), received the highest first week sales for a debut Spanish album in the United States. Following a relatively unsuccessful period, she returned to prominence in 2011 with her appearance as a judge on ''[[American Idol]]'' and released her seventh studio album ''[[Love?]]''. From 2016 to 2018, she starred in the [[police show|police drama]] series ''[[Shades of Blue (TV series)|Shades of Blue]]'' and performed a residency show, [[Jennifer Lopez: All I Have]], at [[Planet Hollywood Las Vegas]]. Lopez also produced and served as a judge on ''[[World of Dance (TV series)|World of Dance]]'' (2017–2020). In 2019, she garnered critical acclaim for her performance as a stripper in the crime drama ''[[Hustlers (film)|Hustlers]]''.

Lopez is considered a [[pop icon|pop culture icon]], and is often described as a [[Triple threat (entertainer)|triple threat entertainer]].<ref name="BBMAs 2014" /><ref name="People Magazine Awards" /><ref name="Time Review" /> With a cumulative film gross of US$3.1 billion and estimated global sales of 70 million records, Lopez is regarded as the most influential Latin entertainer in North America. In 2012, ''[[Forbes]]'' ranked her as the most powerful celebrity in the world, as well as the 38th most powerful woman in the world.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goudreau|first1=Jenna|title=The World's Most Powerful Women: 16 New Faces|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jennagoudreau/2012/08/22/worlds-most-powerful-women-new-faces-jennifer-lopez-laurene-powell-jobs/|website=[[Forbes]]|access-date=November 23, 2016|date=August 22, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' listed her among the [[Time 100|100 most influential people in the world]] in 2018. Her most successful singles on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] include: "[[If You Had My Love]]", "[[I'm Real (Jennifer Lopez song)|I'm Real]]", "[[Ain't It Funny (Murder Remix)|Ain't It Funny]]", "[[All I Have (song)|All I Have]]", and "[[On the Floor]]".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Letkemann |first1=Jessica |title=Jennifer Lopez's Top 10 Biggest Billboard Hits |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/list/6091769/jennifer-lopez-top-10-songs-biggest-billboard-hits |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=June 29, 2018 |date=May 15, 2014 |archive-date=June 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623051957/https://www.billboard.com/articles/list/6091769/jennifer-lopez-top-10-songs-biggest-billboard-hits |url-status=dead }}</ref> For her contributions to the recording industry, Lopez has received a landmark star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], the [[Billboard Icon Award|''Billboard'' Icon Award]], and the [[Michael Jackson Video Vanguard Award]] among other honors. Her other ventures include beauty and clothing lines, fragrances, a [[Nuyorican Productions|production company]], and a [[Lopez Family Foundation|charitable foundation]].

==Early life==
Jennifer Lynn Lopez was born on July 24, 1969, in New York City and was raised in the [[Castle Hill, Bronx|Castle Hill]] neighborhood of the [[Bronx]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courttv.com/trials/puffy/docs/duty-caps_3.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209202541/http://www.courttv.com/trials/puffy/docs/duty-caps_3.html|archive-date=February 9, 2008|title=Duty Captain's Report|access-date=October 29, 2006|publisher=[[Court TV]] |date=January 17, 2001}}</ref><ref name="Gallick2003">{{harvnb|Gallick|2003}}</ref><ref name=biography.com>{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/jennifer-lopez-9542231|title=Jennifer Lopez: Actress, Reality Television Star, Dancer, Singer (1969–)|website=[[Biography.com]]|publisher=[[A&E Networks]]|access-date=February 11, 2019}}</ref> Her parents, David López and Guadalupe Rodríguez, were born in Puerto Rico and emigrated to the United States as children.<ref name=Cartlidge-book>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/jenniferlopez0000cart|url-access=registration| title=Jennifer Lopez|first=Cherese |last=Cartlidge|page=[https://archive.org/details/jenniferlopez0000cart/page/13 13]| publisher=Lucent Books|year=2012|isbn=978-1420507553|quote=Jennifer Lynn Lopez's parents, David and Guadalupe, were both born in Ponce, the second-largest city in Puerto Rico. They immigrated as children to the United States with their families...}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.today.com/parents/jennifer-lopez-opens-about-her-dad-he-was-just-proud-t99971|title=Jennifer Lopez opens up about her dad: 'He was just proud of me'|work=[[Today (US TV show)|Today]]|date=June 22, 2016|access-date= February 11, 2019| first=Randee |last=Dawn}}</ref> After serving in the army, David worked as a computer technician at [[The Guardian Life Insurance Company of America|Guardian Insurance Company]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rodriguez |first1=Giovanni René |title=JLo's Dad Lends A Hand In Silicon Valley |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/giovannirodriguez/2013/09/22/jlos-dad-lends-a-hand-in-silicon-valley/?sh=444ffbb75c34 |access-date=6 June 2021 |work=Forbes |language=en}}</ref> Guadalupe was a homemaker for the first ten years of Lopez's life and later worked as a [[Tupperware]] salesperson<ref name="HuffPost">{{cite news |title=J.Lo Opens Up About Her Parents' Divorce |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/jennifer-lopez_n_3569932 |access-date=6 June 2021 |work=HuffPost |date=2013-07-10 |language=en}}</ref> and as a kindergarten and gym teacher.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/nice-jennifer-lopez-give-kids-free-health-care-not-old-block-article-1.439341 |access-date=6 June 2021}}</ref><ref name="youtube.com">{{cite news |title=Jennifer Lopez In A Candid And Revealing Look At The Most Defining Moments Of Her Life |url=https://youtube.com/qRXX5bNHUuw |access-date=6 June 2021 |language=en}}</ref> (David and Guadalupe divorced in the 1990s after 33 years of marriage.)<ref name="HuffPost"/>

Lopez is a middle child; she has an older sister, Leslie, and a younger sister, [[Lynda Lopez|Lynda]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.terra.com/musica/fotos/mamas_y_mamacitas/64457 |title=Mamás y Mamacitas – Música |publisher=[[Terra Networks]] |access-date=May 24, 2012 |date=May 11, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130124164347/http://www.terra.com/musica/fotos/mamas_y_mamacitas/64457 |archive-date=January 24, 2013 |url-status=dead }}{{failed verification|date=January 2021}}</ref> The three sisters shared a bedroom.<ref name=wmagazine>{{cite news |title=Jennifer Lopez: Dream Girl |url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/jennifer-lopez-august-2013-cover |access-date=7 June 2021 |work=W Magazine |language=en}}</ref> Lopez has described her upbringing as "strict".<ref name=robinson>{{cite news |last1=Robinson |first1=Lisa |title=Jenny Back on the Block |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2011/09/jennifer-lopez-201109 |access-date=6 June 2021 |work=Vanity Fair}}</ref> She was raised in a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] family; she attended Mass every Sunday<ref name=actorsstudio>{{cite news |work=Inside the Actor's Studio (2004)}}</ref> and received a Catholic education, attending Holy Family School and the all-girls [[Preston High School (New York City)|Preston High School]].<ref name=tca>Stated on ''[[Inside the Actors Studio]]'', 2004</ref> In school, Lopez [[Track and field|ran track]] on a national level, participated in gymnastics, and was a member of the softball team.<ref name=rantrack>{{cite book|last=Parish|first=James-Robert|title=Jennifer Lopez: Actor and Singer|page=14|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lh1Y2OK-VdsC&q=J-Lo%3A+The+Secret+Behind+Jennifer+Lopez%27s+Clib+to+the+Top&pg=PA129|isbn=978-0-8160-5832-7|date=November 30, 2005}}</ref><ref name=atriplethreat/> She danced in school musicals and played a leading role in a production of ''[[Godspell]]''.<ref name=behind/>

There was "lots of music" in the typically Puerto Rican household,<ref>{{cite news |title=Jennifer Lopez on her burgeoning film career |url=https://ew.com/article/1995/12/01/jennifer-lopez-her-burgeoning-film-career/ |access-date=6 July 2021 |work=EW.com |language=en}}</ref> and Lopez and her sisters were encouraged to sing, dance and create their own plays for family events.<ref name=behind/><ref name="atriplethreat">{{cite web |url=http://www.evancarmichael.com/Famous-Entrepreneurs/619/The-Triple-Threat-Jennifer-Lopez-is-Born.html |title=The Triple Threat: Jennifer Lopez is Born |publisher=Evan Carmichael |access-date=March 23, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226091637/http://www.evancarmichael.com/Famous-Entrepreneurs/619/The-Triple-Threat-Jennifer-Lopez-is-Born.html |archive-date=February 26, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''[[West Side Story]]'' made a particular impression on the young Lopez and she wanted to be an entertainer from an early age.<ref name=actorsstudio/> At the age of five, she began taking dance lessons at [[Ballet Hispánico]] on the Upper West Side.<ref name=chuck>{{cite news |last1=Arnold |first1=Chuck |title=How NYC made Jennifer Lopez into the superstar she is at 50 |url=https://nypost.com/2019/07/11/how-nyc-made-jennifer-lopez-into-the-superstar-she-is-at-50/ |access-date=6 June 2021 |work=New York Post |date=2019-07-12}}</ref> As a teenager, she learned flamenco, jazz and ballet at the [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Kips Bay Boys & Girls Club]]<ref name=actorsstudio/> and taught dance to younger students, including [[Kerry Washington]].<ref>{{cite news |title=EXCLUSIVE: Kerry Washington Reflects on Her Bronx Childhood, Dishes on Husband's Hilarious Met Gala Antics {{!}} Entertainment Tonight |url=https://www.etonline.com/news/216634_exclusive_kerry_washington_reflects_on_her_bronx_childhood_dishes_on_husband_s_hilarious_met_gala_antics |access-date=11 June 2021 |work=www.etonline.com}}</ref> After graduating high school, Lopez had a part-time secretarial job at a law firm<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kochman |first1=Ben |title=Former employer raffles J.Lo concert tix to help pop star’s old school – Bronx Times |url=https://www.bxtimes.com/former-employer-raffles-j-lo-concert-tix-to-help-pop-stars-old-school/ |access-date=11 June 2021 |work=www.bxtimes.com}}</ref><ref name=actorsstudio/> and studied business at New York's [[Baruch College]] for one semester.<ref name=chuck/><ref name=behind/> At the age of 18, Lopez enrolled as a full-time student at Manhattan's Phil Black Dance Studio, where she had already been taking night classes in jazz and tap dance.<ref name=robinson/><ref name=wmagazine/><ref name=actorsstudio/> Her parents were unhappy with her decision to leave college to pursue a career as a professional dancer.<ref name=behind/> Her mother asked her to move out of the family home and they stopped speaking for eight months.<ref name=behind/><ref>{{cite news |last1=May 10 |first1=seattlepi com staff on |title=Jennifer Lopez credits Barry Manilow with saving relationship with mom |url=https://blog.seattlepi.com/people/2011/05/10/jennifer-lopez-credits-barry-manilow-with-saving-relationship-with-mom/ |access-date=12 June 2021 |work=Celebrities and Entertainment News |date=2011-05-10}}</ref> Lopez moved to Manhattan, sleeping in the dance studio's office for the first few months.<ref name=robinson/><ref name=wmagazine/><ref name=actorsstudio/>

== Career ==
===1989–1996: Professional dancing and early acting roles===
Lopez's first professional job came in 1989 when she spent five months touring Europe with the musical revue show ''Golden Musicals of Broadway''. She was the only member of the [[Ensemble (musical theatre)|chorus]] not to have a solo and later characterized it as a pivotal moment where she realized the importance of a "tough skin" in the entertainment business.<ref>{{cite news |title=BBC Radio 1 - Jennifer Lopez with Scott Mills |url=https://youtube.com/yyvATdAUjr0 |access-date=12 June 2021 |language=en}}</ref> In 1990, she danced alongside [[MC Hammer]] in an episode of ''[[Yo! MTV Raps]]''<ref>{{cite news |title=Jennifer Lopez left red-faced! |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/jennifer-lopez-left-red-faced/story-45GFPXACpySC1FPPAFpXcI.html |access-date=15 June 2021 |work=Hindustan Times |date=2010-04-25 |language=en}}</ref> and traveled around Japan for four months as a chorus member in ''Synchronicity''.<ref name=actorsstudio/> When she returned to the United States, she was hired as a backup dancer for [[New Kids on the Block]]'s performance of "[[Games (New Kids on the Block song)|Games]]" at the [[American Music Awards of 1991|1991 American Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Perricon|first=Kathleen|title=Jennifer Lopez dances with New Kids on the Block in 1991 video clip|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2011-05-10/entertainment/29547058_1_nkotb-music-video-new-kids|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=June 22, 2012|date=May 10, 2011}}</ref> She also traveled around America as part of regional productions of the musicals ''[[Jesus Christ Superstar]]'' and ''[[Oklahoma!]]''<ref>{{cite news |title=Jennifer Lopez The Crossover Dream Comes True |url=https://www.bmi.com/news/entry/19991101jennifer_lopez_jennifer_lopez_the_crossover_dream_comes_true |access-date=12 June 2021 |work=BMI.com |date=1999-10-31 |language=en}}</ref> During this period, Lopez also danced in music videos including [[Doug E. Fresh]]'s "Summertime", Richard Rogers' "Can't Stop Loving You", [[EPMD]]'s "[[Rampage (song)|Rampage]]"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reid |first1=Shaheem |title=Is that really LL Cool J in EPMD's "Rampage" video? Parrish addresses an urban legend |url=https://www.revolt.tv/2017/9/28/20820481/is-that-really-ll-cool-j-in-epmd-s-rampage-video-parrish-addresses-an-urban-legend |access-date=15 June 2021 |work=REVOLT |date=2017-09-28 |language=en}}</ref> and [[Samantha Fox]]'s "[[(Hurt Me! Hurt Me!) But the Pants Stay On]]".<ref>{{cite news |title=https://twitter.com/samfoxcom/status/203078282353197056 |url=https://twitter.com/SamFoxCom/status/203078282353197056 |access-date=6 July 2021 |work=Twitter |language=en}}</ref>

Lopez's most high-profile job as a professional dancer was as a [[List of In Living Color cast members#Fly Girls (house dance troupe)|Fly Girl]] on the sketch comedy television series ''[[In Living Color]]'', which starred comedians including [[Jamie Foxx]] and [[Jim Carrey]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Arnold |first1=Chuck |title=Remember when J.Lo was a ‘Fly Girl’? |url=https://nypost.com/2018/08/20/remember-when-j-lo-was-a-fly-girl/ |access-date=5 July 2021 |work=New York Post |date=20 August 2018}}</ref> At the New York audition, the show's choreographer, [[Rosie Perez]], noticed that Lopez had "star quality" and "did not complain, not once" when asked to repeatedly perform the dance routine.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fat Joe Live (Feat. Rosie Perez) |url=https://youtube.com/--OC4L-bykk |access-date=5 July 2021 |language=en}}</ref> Lopez moved to Los Angeles in late 1991 for the job; she filmed ''In Living Color'' during the day and attended acting classes taught by Aaron Speiser at night.<ref name=actorsstudio/> After appearing as a Fly Girl in seasons three and four of the show, Lopez left to work as a backup dancer for [[Janet Jackson]], and appeared in the music video for “[[That's the Way Love Goes (Janet Jackson song)|That’s the Way Love Goes]]”.<ref>{{cite news|last=Morales|first=Ed|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1999/may/30/entertainment/ca-42339|title=It's Not La Vida Loca to Her|access-date=January 30, 2012|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=May 30, 1999}}</ref> She was scheduled to tour with Jackson on her [[Janet World Tour]] in late 1993 but opted to pursue an acting career instead.<ref>{{cite news|title=Living Single|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gCYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA100|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]] |access-date=July 6, 2012|page=100|date=May 2001}}</ref>

Lopez's first professional acting job was a small recurring role on the television show ''[[South Central (TV series)|South Central]]'' (1994). She was invited to audition for the pilot by a casting director who had seen her speak to camera during a behind-the-scenes ''In Living Color'' segment.<ref name=actorsstudio/> Lopez then acquired an agent and was cast in the [[CBS]] show ''[[Second Chances (American TV series)|Second Chances]]'' and its spin-off ''[[Hotel Malibu]]''. She appeared in the direct-to-video drama film ''[[Lost in the Wild]]'' (1993).<ref name="Rovi Lost in the Wild">{{cite web |first=Sandra |last=Brennan |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/lost-in-the-wild-v160416 |title=Lost in the Wild – Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |work=[[AllRovi]] |access-date=October 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130101194205/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/lost-in-the-wild-v160416 |archive-date=January 1, 2013 }}</ref> For her first major movie role, in [[Gregory Nava]]'s 1995 drama ''[[My Family (film)|My Family]]'',<ref name="Rovi My Family">{{cite web|first=Matthew |last=Tobey |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/my-family-v133610 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013110908/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/my-family-v133610 |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 13, 2011 |title=My Family – Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |work=AllRovi |access-date=October 30, 2011 }}</ref> Lopez received a nomination for the [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Supporting Female|Independent Spirit Award for Best Supporting Actress]].<ref name="Rovi My Family" /> Lopez then starred in the action comedy ''[[Money Train]]'' (1995). Kenneth Turan of the ''Los Angeles Times'' said she "mostly holds her own" with co-stars [[Wesley Snipes]] and [[Woody Harrelson]],<ref>{{cite news |title=MOVIE REVIEW : Action and Rapport Keep 'Money Train' on Track |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1995-11-22-ca-5884-story.html |access-date=6 July 2021 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=22 November 1995}}</ref> while Stephen Holden of ''The New York Times'' praised her "scene-stealing charm".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Holden |first1=Stephen |title=FILM REVIEW;Underground Fun House With the Basketball Duo |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/22/movies/film-review-underground-fun-house-with-the-basketball-duo.html |access-date=6 July 2021 |work=The New York Times |date=22 November 1995}}</ref> In 1996, Lopez had a supporting role opposite [[Robin Williams]] in the comedy ''[[Jack (1996 film)|Jack]]''.<ref name="Rovi Jack">{{cite web|first=Clarke |last=Fountain |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/jack-v136486 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205192220/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/jack-v136486 |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 5, 2012 |title=Jack – Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |publisher=AllRovi |access-date=October 30, 2011 }}</ref> Lopez next starred opposite [[Jack Nicholson]] in the neo-noir thriller ''[[Blood and Wine]]'' (1997).<ref name="Rovi Blood and Wine">{{cite web|first=Sandra |last=Brennan |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/blood-and-wine-v136830 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111222145458/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/blood-and-wine-v136830 |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 22, 2011 |title=Blood and Wine – Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |publisher=AllRovi |access-date=October 30, 2011 }}</ref> David Rooney of ''Variety'' felt Lopez delivered in "juggling" the "smoldering and soulful sides" of the character<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rooney |first1=David |title=Blood and Wine |url=https://variety.com/1996/film/reviews/blood-and-wine-1200446651/ |access-date=7 July 2021 |work=Variety |date=24 September 1996}}</ref> while Lisa Schwarzbaum of ''Entertainment Weekly'' said she was "used as a place marker rather than as a real girl."<ref>{{cite news |title=Blood and Wine {{!}} Movie Review {{!}} Entertainment Weekly |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,286954,00.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070331151624/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,286954,00.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2007-03-31 |access-date=7 July 2021 |date=31 March 2007}}</ref>

===1997–1999: Breakthrough with ''Selena'' and ''On the 6''===
Lopez starred as the title role of the [[Selena]] biopic [[Selena (film)|of the same name]] in March.<ref name="Rovi Selena">{{cite web |first=Mark |last=Deming |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/selena-v154769 |title=Selena – Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |publisher=AllRovi |access-date=October 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130110155611/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/selena-v154769 |archive-date=January 10, 2013 }}</ref> Despite having previously worked with the film's director on ''My Family'', Lopez was subjected to an intense auditioning process before she was cast in the film.<ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press|title=Lopez gets Selena role|newspaper=Dallas Morning News |date=June 14, 1996}}</ref> [[Kenneth Turan]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' stated that even in the "forgettable films" ''Money Train'' and ''Jack'', Lopez's "presence and ability made her seem just one role away from stardom" and with ''Selena'' she's "seized the opportunity and turned in an incandescent presentation that is especially strong during the film's numerous musical numbers". He concluded by calling the film not just a celebration of Selena's life, but also of the actress who portrayed her.<ref name="She's Seen in the Best Light">{{cite news |author=Kenneth Turan |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1997-03-21/entertainment/ca-40367_1_selena-quintanilla-perez |title=In the Authorized 'Selena,' She's Seen in the Best Light|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=October 10, 1995 |access-date=December 10, 2012}}</ref> The announcement was described as the "role of a lifetime" from news outlets and Lopez's salary for the film was reported at US$1 million,<ref>{{cite news|last=Jakle|first=Jeanne|title=Selena star says yes to role as fiancee|newspaper=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|date=October 30, 1996}}</ref><ref name="La">{{cite news |title='Mi Familia' actress Jennifer Lopez to play Selena in movie|work=[[Austin-American Statesman]] |date=June 15, 1996}}</ref> which made Lopez the highest-paid Hispanic actress in history. After filming ''Selena'', Lopez was "really feeling [her] Latin roots" and cut a demo in Spanish.<ref>Mendible, M. (2007). "From bananas to buttocks: the Latina body in popular film and culture". Austin: [[University of Texas Press]]. Retrieved September 4, 2012.</ref> Lopez's manager then sent the song, titled "Vivir Sin Ti" (Living without You), to [[Sony Music|Sony Music Entertainment]]'s [[Work Group]], who showed an interest in signing Lopez. [[Tommy Mottola]], the head of the label suggested to her that she sing in English instead.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TxIEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA27 |page=27 | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | volume=119 | issn=0006-2510 | number=5 | title=On the Down Lo |date=February 3, 2007 |access-date=July 1, 2012}}</ref>

In April 1997, Lopez starred in the horror film ''[[Anaconda (film)|Anaconda]]'' alongside [[Ice Cube]] and [[Jon Voight]].<ref name="Rovi Anaconda">{{cite web |first=Mark |last=Deming |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/anaconda-v154826 |title=Anaconda – Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |publisher=AllRovi |access-date=October 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004083933/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/anaconda-v154826 |archive-date=October 4, 2011 }}</ref> Lopez starred alongside [[Sean Penn]] and [[Billy Bob Thornton]] in the crime film ''[[U Turn (1997 film)|U Turn]]'', in October 1997. The film, which is based on the novel ''Stray Dogs'' by [[John Ridley]], received somewhat positive reviews from critics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/u-turn |title=U Turn |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=December 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130102223528/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/u-turn/ |archive-date=January 2, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In June 1998, Lopez starred opposite [[George Clooney]] in ''[[Out of Sight]]'', [[Steven Soderbergh]]'s adaptation of [[Elmore Leonard]]'s [[Out of Sight (novel)|novel]] of the same name.<ref name="Rovi Out of Sight">{{cite web |first=Bhob |last=Stewart |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/out-of-sight-v162749 |title=Out of Sight – Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |publisher=AllRovi |access-date=October 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111030025835/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/out-of-sight-v162749 |archive-date=October 30, 2011 }}</ref> Cast as a deputy federal marshal who falls for a charming criminal, Lopez won rave reviews for her performance.<ref name="nydailynews1998">{{cite news|last=Kehr |first=Dave |title=Clooney & Lopez Are Lovable At First 'Sight' George Plays A Bank Robber Who Steals Jennifer's Heart |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/nydn-features/clooney-lopez-lovable-sight-george-plays-bank-robber-steals-jennifer-heart-article-1.802614 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130920194255/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/nydn-features/clooney-lopez-lovable-sight-george-plays-bank-robber-steals-jennifer-heart-article-1.802614 |archive-date=September 20, 2013 |work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|location=New York |access-date=January 30, 2012 |date=June 26, 1998 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lopez provided the voice of Azteca in the computer-animated film ''[[Antz]]'' in October 1998.<ref name="Rovi Antz">{{cite web |first=Bhob |last=Stewart |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/antz-v173454 |title=Antz – Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |publisher=AllRovi |access-date=October 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119174245/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/antz-v173454 |archive-date=January 19, 2012 }}</ref>

Lopez's debut single, "[[If You Had My Love]]", was released in May 1999, as she began to ready her first album.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jennifer Lopez Readies First Album|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | date=April 15, 1999 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=348&dat=20010130&id=0cYvAAAAIBAJ&pg=1737,9846654|title=Jennifer Lopez release proves to be a good Latin-soul album|author=Brian McCollum|newspaper=[[Rome News-Tribune]] |date=January 30, 2001|access-date=January 15, 2010}}</ref> Lopez became the first artist to top the ''[[Billboard Hot 100]]'' with a debut single since [[Britney Spears]] did so with her single "[[...Baby One More Time (song)|...Baby One More Time]]" four months prior.<ref name="billboardno1issue">{{cite book|title=Billboard Magazine Vol. 111, No. 24|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uw0EAAAAMBAJ|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media, Inc.]]|access-date=July 2, 2012|page=90|date=June 12, 1999}}</ref> Her debut album was named ''[[On the 6]]'', to reflect the [[6 (New York City Subway service)|New York City Subway rail line]] connecting her home in the Bronx to work in Manhattan. During production of the album, Lopez was made aware that she received her recording contract on the basis of her looks and an already established name in the entertainment industry, and she wanted to prove she had musical talent.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1ZGMcUEvkyEC&pg=PA104 |title=Alicia Keys, Ashanti, Beyoncé, Destiny's Child, Jennifer Lopez & Mya: Divas of the New Millennium |date=June 1, 2005 |access-date=July 1, 2012|isbn=9780974977966|page=104|author1=Stacy Deanne |author2=Kelly Kenyatta |author3=Natasha Lowery |author4=Kwynn Sanders |publisher=Amber Books Publishing}}</ref> Prior to the debut of her music, critics wondered why she would take the risk of launching a music career. It was noted that: "If the album was a flop, not only would it embarrass Lopez, but it might even damage her career."<ref name="Latin Sensations">{{cite book|last=Marquez|first=Herón|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q1BW88v0_zMC&pg=PA47 |title=Latin Sensations | page=47 |publisher=Twenty-First Century Books |date=January 1, 2001 |access-date=July 3, 2012| isbn=9780822549932}}</ref> "[[Waiting for Tonight]]", the third single from ''On the 6'', is widely considered to be Lopez's best song.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stack|first=Tim|title=Jennifer Lopez: 'Waiting for Tonight' was awesome...but it might be time to stop singing|url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2009/11/23/jennifer-lopez-waiting-for-tonight-was-amazing-but-its-time-to-stop-singing/|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=March 10, 2012|date=November 23, 2009}}</ref> Lopez's musical success came as a surprise to critics; its launch made the "popular actor even more popular". Both the music industry and the public became intrigued by "this woman who seemed to have so many different talents".<ref name="Latin Sensations"/> By the end of 1999, Lopez successfully converted herself from a film star to a pop star.<ref>{{cite news|title=Puff Daddy out on bail|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/579912.stm|work=BBC News|access-date=July 3, 2012|date=December 28, 1999}}</ref> She joined a select few in achieving this feat, becoming the first since [[Vanessa Williams]] (1992) and [[Martika]] (1989).<ref name="billboardno1issue" />

===2000–2002: Film success, ''J.Lo'' and ''This Is Me... Then'' ===

On February 23, 2000, Lopez, accompanied by then-boyfriend [[Sean Combs]], wore a plunging exotic [[Green Versace dress of Jennifer Lopez|green Versace silk chiffon dress]] on the [[red carpet]] of the [[42nd Annual Grammy Awards]]. The dress "had a low-cut neck that extended several inches below her navel, where it was loosely fastened with a sparkly [[brooch]] and then opened out again," exposing her [[midriff]] and then as cut along the front of the legs like a bath robe.<ref name="PhillipsReay2002">{{cite book|editor1-last=Phillips|editor-first=Kim M.|editor2-last=Reay|editor2-first=Barry|title=Sexualities in history: a reader|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Cz3bPMw_7h4C&pg=PA407|last=Barrera|first=Magdalena|chapter=Hottentot 2000: ''Jennifer Lopez and Her Butt''|year=2002|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415929356|page=407}}</ref> The dress generated controversy and media attention, with images of Lopez in the dress being downloaded from the Grammy website over half a million times within 24 hours of the event.<ref name="Lee2003">{{cite book|last=Lee|first=Michelle|title=Fashion victim: our love-hate relationship with dressing, shopping, and the cost of style|url=https://archive.org/details/fashionvictim00mich|url-access=registration|access-date=May 16, 2011|date=February 11, 2003|publisher=Broadway Books|isbn=978-0-7679-1048-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/fashionvictim00mich/page/122 122]}}</ref> Lopez was surprised by the enormous media coverage, declaring that she had no idea "it was going to become such a big deal".<ref name="OTD">{{cite web|url=http://onthisdayinfashion.com/?p=11475|title=J.Lo Helps Put Donatella—and Herself—on the Fashion Map in That Green Dress|publisher=On This Day in Fashion|date=February 23, 2001|last=Chambers|first=Rachel|access-date=May 16, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823180305/http://onthisdayinfashion.com/?p=11475|archive-date=August 23, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Lopez returned to the big screen in August 2000, starring in the psychological thriller ''[[The Cell]]'' opposite [[Vincent D'Onofrio]].<ref name="Rovi Cell">{{cite web |first=Mark |last=Deming |url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/the-cell-v195764 |title=The Cell – Cast, Reviews, Summary, and Awards |publisher=AllRovi |access-date=October 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120126085216/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/the-cell-v195764 |archive-date=January 26, 2012 }}</ref>

During the process of recording her second album, Lopez decided to tweak her image as she began to develop into a [[sex symbol]]. She started going by J.Lo, something fans often called her<ref name="BookJLo">{{cite book|title=Divas of the new Millennium|year=2005|page=108|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1ZGMcUEvkyEC&q=Jennifer+Lopez+if+you+had+my+love&pg=PA104|last1=Deanne|first1=Stacy|last2=Kenyatta|first2=Kelly|last3=Lowery|first3=Natasha|last4=Sanders|first4=Kwynn|isbn=9780974977966|access-date=November 10, 2015}}</ref> in the years after director [[Oliver Stone]] coined the term on the set of the 1997 film ''U Turn''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/5-unfiltered-facts-about-oliver-stone-courtesy-of-oliver-stone-214610705.html|title=5 Unfiltered Facts About Oliver Stone, Courtesy of Oliver Stone|website=www.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> She subsequently named the album ''[[J.Lo (album)|J.Lo]]''. Released on January 23, 2001, it was a commercial success, debuting at number one on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref name=dethroned>{{cite web|title=Lopez Bows At No. 1; O-Town, Dream Debut High5|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/80647/lopez-bows-at-no-1-o-town-dream-debut-high5|work=Billboard |date=January 2001|access-date=June 18, 2013}}</ref> During the same week, her romantic comedy film ''[[The Wedding Planner]]'' in which she starred opposite [[Matthew McConaughey]] opened atop the box office. This made her the first woman to have a number one film and album simultaneously in the United States.<ref name="timeTyrangiel">{{cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2008201_2008200_2008207,00.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090301064251/http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0%2C8599%2C1093638%2C00.html |archive-date=March 1, 2009 |title=Jennifer Lopez |author=Josh Tyrangiel |access-date=January 13, 2007 |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=August 13, 2005 |url-status=dead |author-link=Josh Tyrangiel }}</ref> The album was preceded by the release of its lead single, "[[Love Don't Cost a Thing (song)|Love Don't Cost a Thing]]", which reached number one on the ''Billboard'' [[Mainstream Top 40]] chart. It was followed by the single "[[Play (Jennifer Lopez song)|Play]]".<ref name="I'm Real ET" /> In April 2001, Lopez launched [[J.Lo by Jennifer Lopez]], her own clothing and accessory company. Lopez felt that "the voluptuous woman [was] almost ignored" in the [[fashion industry]], and therefore her company specialized in clothing women of all shapes.<ref name="BookJLo" /> The following month, she starred in the romantic drama film ''[[Angel Eyes (film)|Angel Eyes]]'', which performed disappointingly at the box office and generated mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lopez is simply out of sight in 'Angel Eyes'|newspaper=[[The Detroit News]] |date=May 18, 2001}}</ref> After several months, ''J.Lo'' was declining on the charts; this prompted Mottola to recruit rapper [[Ja Rule]] to create an urban-oriented remix of the song "[[I'm Real (Jennifer Lopez song)|I'm Real]]". This led to the release of "I'm Real (Murder Remix)", which quickly reached number one on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100. Its success resulted in ''J.Lo'' being reissued to include the single, which was number one in the United States during the week of the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref name="I'm Real ET">{{cite web|last1=Azzopardi|first1=Chris|title=Jennifer Lopez's 'I'm Real' 15 Years Later: How the Rule-Breaking Duet With Ja Rule Prevented a Sophomore Slump|url=http://www.etonline.com/features/196835_jennifer_lopez_im_real_oral_history/|website=[[ETonline]]|publisher=CBS Studios, Inc.|access-date=November 23, 2016|date=September 1, 2016}}</ref> ''J.Lo'' became the best-selling album of Lopez's career, having sold 3.8 million copies in the US and moved over 12 million units worldwide.<ref name="New Epic Deal" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blastro.com/artist/Jennifer+Lopez.html#artist-bio-full|title=Jennifer Lopez {{!}} Music Videos, News, Photos, Tour Dates {{!}} Blastro|website=[[Blastro]]|access-date=October 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927011527/http://www.blastro.com/artist/Jennifer+Lopez.html#artist-bio-full|archive-date=September 27, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>

Having redefined Lopez's sound with "I'm Real (Murder Remix)", Epic decided to release further remixes in order to "keep the momentum going".<ref name="Billboard Book of Number One Hits">{{cite book|last=Bronson|first=Fred|title=The Billboard Book of Number One Hits|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PgGqNrqfrsoC&pg=PT931|edition=5|year=2003|publisher=Crown|isbn=9780823076772|page=922}}</ref> A remix album entitled ''[[J to tha L–O! The Remixes]]'' was subsequently released on February 5, 2002. It debuted at the summit of the ''Billboard'' 200, making it the first remix album to do so. Its lead single, "[[Ain't It Funny (Murder Remix)]]", featuring Ja Rule and Caddillac Tah, reached number one in the US.<ref>{{cite web|title=J. Lo Nabs Double No. 1s|date=March 9, 2002|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/76640/j-lo-nabs-double-no-1s|access-date=April 9, 2013|work=Billboard, Inc}}</ref> ''J to tha L–O! The Remixes'' became one of the [[List of best-selling remix albums|best-selling remix albums]] of all time, selling 1.5 million copies in the US.<ref name="album sales">{{cite web|last=Trust|first=Gary|title=Ask Billboard: Analyzing 'American Idol'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/955571/ask-billboard-analyzing-american-idol|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=January 29, 2012|date=October 1, 2010}}</ref> It produced two more singles: "[[I'm Gonna Be Alright]]" and "[[Alive (Jennifer Lopez song)|Alive]]", a ballad co-written by her husband at the time, [[Cris Judd]]. In April 2002, Lopez opened her restaurant, Madrè's.<ref name="BookJLo" /> The following month, she starred in the thriller film ''[[Enough (film)|Enough]]'', which was described by the ''[[Boston Herald]]'' as a "kick-butt, female empowerment" film.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schaefer|first=Stephen|title=Movies: Singer-actress Jennifer Lopez shows her strength in thriller 'Enough'|newspaper=[[Boston Herald]] |date=May 19, 2002|location=Boston}}</ref> While filming ''Enough'', which required an overworked Lopez to practice [[Krav Maga]], she suffered a [[Mental breakdown|nervous breakdown]]. She recalled feeling "sick and weird", refusing therapeutic help or medication. She confessed, "I was like – I don't want to move, I don't want to talk, I don't want to do anything."<ref>{{cite news|last=Singh|first=Anita|title=Jennifer Lopez: I had a nervous breakdown|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/3152788/Jennifer-Lopez-I-had-a-nervous-breakdown.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |access-date=October 20, 2012|date=October 7, 2008}}</ref> In September, she released her first fragrance, [[Glow by JLo]]. It performed strongly despite predictions that it would fail, and became the top-selling fragrance in the US.<ref name=HS>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qki6zZ4aWd0C&q=Glow+by+JLo&pg=PA6-IA135 |title=Beauty Imagined:A History of the Global Beauty Industry|first=Geoffrey|last=Jones |publisher=Oxford University Press|date=February 25, 2010 |access-date=October 22, 2012|isbn=9780191609619}}</ref>

Lopez's third studio album, ''[[This Is Me... Then]]'', was released on November 25, 2002. It was dedicated to actor [[Ben Affleck]], her fiancé at the time. The album's lead single "[[Jenny from the Block]]", was later described by Sam Lansky of [[MTV News]] as her most iconic single.<ref name="MTV Lansky">{{cite web|last1=Lansky|first1=Sam|title=Jennifer Lopez Is Back On Top With 'Love?' Which Is Exactly Where She Deserves To Be|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2012/04/19/jennifer-lopez-love-on-the-floor-dance-again/|website=[[MTV Buzzworthy]]|access-date=September 25, 2015|date=April 19, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928224759/http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2012/04/19/jennifer-lopez-love-on-the-floor-dance-again/|archive-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref> In the song, Lopez "intones her modest childhood roots".<ref name=dedication>{{cite news|title=J-Lo disc declares her love|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/11/27/1038274342213.html|newspaper=[[The Age]] |access-date=January 29, 2012|date=November 27, 2002|location=Melbourne, Australia}}</ref> The album itself performed strongly, selling 2.6 million copies in the US.<ref name="album sales" /> Its second single, "[[All I Have (song)|All I Have]]", peaked at number one in the US. That December, Lopez starred opposite [[Ralph Fiennes]] in the romantic comedy ''[[Maid in Manhattan]]'', which became the highest-grossing film of her career.<ref name="BOM Breakdown" />

===2003–2005: Continued film success and ''Rebirth''===

[[File:JenniferLopez.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Lopez arriving at the [[2004 MTV Video Music Awards|MTV Video Music Awards]], August 2004]]

In August 2003, Lopez starred opposite Affleck in the romantic comedy ''[[Gigli]]''. The film was a [[box office bomb]] and is considered [[List of films considered the worst|one of the worst films of all time]]. The film's poor reception was attributed to negative press preceding its release, as well as the media attention surrounding Lopez and Affleck's engagement which largely overshadowed the film.<ref name="BOM Breakdown" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stern|first1=Marlow|title=A Look Back at 'Gigli,' the Infamous Bennifer-Starring Film, on Its 10th Anniversary|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/08/01/a-look-back-at-gigli-the-infamous-bennifer-starring-film-on-its-10th-anniversary.html|newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]]|publisher=[[IAC (company)|IAC]]|access-date=October 17, 2016|date=August 1, 2013}}</ref> Lopez would later describe this as the lowest point of her career, saying "[It] was very tough", "the tabloid press had just come into existence at the time, so I was like a poster child for that moment."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tess Katz|first1=Emily|title=Jennifer Lopez Opens Up About 'The Gigli Era': 'It Was Very Tough'|url=https://huffingtonpost.com/entry/jennifer-lopez-gigli_n_6523402|website=[[HuffPost]]|access-date=December 12, 2016|date=January 23, 2015}}</ref> In October of that year, she released her next fragrance, [[Still Jennifer Lopez]]. Lopez also launched her next fashion label, Sweetface. It was described by [[Andy Hilfiger]] as a "more intellectual, more inspirational collection than J-Lo by Jennifer Lopez. Less sporty, more suede."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Freeman|first1=Hadley|title=No more velour: J-Lo label aims upmarket aims for high fashion cred|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2005/feb/11/fashion.shopping|website=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=December 10, 2016|date=February 11, 2005}}</ref> Lopez's clothing lines and two fragrances generated over $300 million in revenue throughout 2004, which made her the 19th richest person under 40.<ref name="timeTyrangiel" />

In March 2004, Lopez had a minor role in the film ''[[Jersey Girl (2004 film)|Jersey Girl]]'', alongside Affleck. Her character, Gertrude Steiney, dies during childbirth within the first 15 minutes of the film. From the intense media scrutiny following the couple's break-up, it was noted that "they may need to put Lopez in a coffin on the poster if they want anyone to come".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/4580539/ns/today-entertainment/t/marketing-jersey-girl-post-gigli-world/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120727005648/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/4580539/ns/today-entertainment/t/marketing-jersey-girl-post-gigli-world/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 27, 2012 |title=Marketing 'Jersey Girl' in a post-'Gigli' world |publisher=MSNBC |date=March 29, 2004 |access-date=October 20, 2012 }}</ref> In October, Lopez co-starred alongside [[Richard Gere]] in the drama ''[[Shall We Dance? (2004 film)|Shall We Dance?]]'', a re-make of the [[Shall We Dance? (1996 film)|1996 Japanese film of the same title]]. The film was successful at the box office, and was considered a rebound for Lopez following ''Gigli''.<ref name="BOM Breakdown">{{cite web|last1=Gray|first1=Brandon|title=Bankability Breakdown: Jennifer Lopez|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2729|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|access-date=October 17, 2016|date=April 22, 2010}}</ref>

After placing her career on hiatus, Lopez released her fourth studio album, ''[[Rebirth (Jennifer Lopez album)|Rebirth]]'', in February 2005. According to Lopez, ''Rebirth'' "came about because I was on such a roller-coaster ride, that was my career from my first album to my last album, and I did a bunch of movie projects in between. I finally took some time just for myself, and [when] I came back, this was the first project I did. I felt like it was a new beginning for me, like I was, in a way, reborn."<ref>{{cite web|last=Goodman |first=Abbey |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1497737/jennifer-lopez-on-rebirth-new-beginning.jhtml |title=Jennifer Lopez Calls Rebirth 'A New Beginning' – Music, Celebrity, Artist News |publisher=MTV News |date=March 3, 2005 |access-date=April 29, 2012}}</ref> Tracy Hopkins of NBC's [[NBC|Today Music]] noted that after "fawning" over Affleck on ''This Is Me... Then''", Lopez "wisely keeps her love life out of the spotlight" on ''Rebirth'' and only references her relationship with singer/actor [[Marc Anthony]] on a few tracks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.today.com/popculture/rebirth-its-best-when-j-lo-keeps-it-dance-floor-wbna7047411 |title='Rebirth' at its best on dance floor |publisher=Today.com |date=February 3, 2005 |access-date=February 8, 2013}}</ref> The album produced the single "[[Get Right (song)|Get Right]]", which peaked at number one in the United Kingdom.<ref name="Latina Chart Hits">{{cite web|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Priscilla|title=Jennifer Lopez's Chart Topping Hits|url=http://www.latina.com/6-15-years-jlo%E2%80%99s-best-hits|website=[[Latina (magazine)|Latina]]|access-date=October 17, 2016|date=June 12, 2014}}</ref> In May, she starred alongside [[Jane Fonda]] in the romantic comedy ''[[Monster-in-Law]]'', for which she received a salary of $15 million.<ref name=fonda>{{cite news|last=Lumenick|first=Lou|title=So Fonda The Fight|newspaper=[[New York Post]]|date=March 13, 2005|page=48}}</ref> The film's marketing played up Lopez's "''Gigli''-and-tabloid tarnished image", and it became a box office success.<ref name="BOM Breakdown" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Lowe|first=Kinsey R.|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2005/may/16/entertainment/et-boxoffice16|title='Monster-in-Law' gets a cheery reception; The comedy with Jane Fonda and Jennifer Lopez debuts at No.1 on another weekend off the pace set in 2004.|access-date=January 30, 2012|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=May 16, 2005|location=Los Angeles, California}}</ref> In August, Lopez starred alongside [[Robert Redford]] and [[Morgan Freeman]] in ''[[An Unfinished Life]]'', a drama film based on the novel of the same name.

===2006–2009: ''Como Ama una Mujer'' and career setbacks===

[[File:Jennifer Lopez 2008.jpg|thumb|upright|Lopez in 2008]]

In April 2006, Lopez reappeared on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 as a featured artist on "[[Control Myself]]", the lead single from [[LL Cool J]]'s twelfth studio album ''[[Todd Smith (album)|Todd Smith]]''. The song peaked at number four on the chart following its release as a [[music download]], making it the pair's second collaboration to reach the top five.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Pietroluongo|first1=Silvio|title=LL Cool J Sees Historic Re-Entry|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=April 29, 2006|volume=118|issue=18|page=46|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media, Inc.]]|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> ''[[Bordertown (2006 film)|Bordertown]]'', a film based on the [[female homicides in Ciudad Juárez]], Mexico, made its premiere at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] on May 18, 2006. Lopez, who also acts as the film's producer, stars as Lauren Adrian, an American news reporter for the Chicago Sentinel who wants to be assigned to the Iraq front-lines to cover the war.<ref>{{cite news|last=Summers|first=Chris|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/5268558.stm|title=Hollywood tackles Mexican mystery|date=September 10, 2006|work=BBC News|access-date=July 24, 2012}}</ref> ''Bordertown'' received a [[direct-to-video]] release.<ref name="BOM Breakdown" /> ''[[DanceLife]]'', a reality series following the lives of seven dancers trying to break into the world of professional dance, aired on MTV from January 15 to March 5, 2007. Lopez produced, created and was featured in the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/shows/dancelife/series.jhtml |title=Dancelife &#124; Full Episodes, Photos, Episode Synopsis and Recaps |publisher=MTV News |access-date=August 8, 2012}}</ref> According to the album's co-producer Estéfano, Lopez's fifth studio album ''[[Como Ama una Mujer]]'' would "prove critics wrong" with its "big songs that require a voice"; referring to the criticism of Lopez having a "limited" vocal tone.<ref name="Contactmusic Rebirth">{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/pages/jenniferlopezx18x03x05|title=Jennifer Lopez – Rebirth – Album Review |publisher=Contactmusic News |access-date=April 1, 2012}}</ref><ref name="Contactmusic Spanish">{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news-article/j.lo-to-prove-critics-wrong-with-spanish-album_30_01_2006 |title=Jennifer Lopez – J.Lo To Prove Critics Wrong With Spanish Album |publisher=Contactmusic News |date=January 30, 2006 |access-date=June 3, 2012}}</ref> The album's lead single "[[Qué Hiciste]]" reached number one on ''Billboard''{{'}}s [[Hot Latin Songs]] chart. Lopez performed the song on the [[American Idol (season 6)|sixth season]] of ''[[American Idol]]'' on April 11, 2007, becoming the first person to perform a Spanish song on the series.<ref name="Latina Chart Hits" /> The album received the highest first-week sales in the United States for a debut Spanish album and the highest digital sales.<ref name="Como Ama Una Mujer Breaks Records">{{cite news |title=Jennifer Lopez's First Spanish-Language Album is an Instant No. 1 on the Billboard Latin Chart |url=http://www.prweb.com/releases/spanish/jennifer/prweb517033.htm |publisher=PRWeb |access-date=January 29, 2012|location=New York|date=April 6, 2007}}</ref><ref name="Billboard Spanish Album 2016" />

In September 2007, Lopez starred in the [[biographical film]] ''[[El Cantante]]'', which is based on the life of the late [[salsa music|salsa]] singer [[Héctor Lavoe]]. In the film, Lavoe is portrayed by then-husband [[Marc Anthony]] while Lopez plays Lavoe's wife Puchi.<ref name="CantanteNYReview">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/03/movies/03cant.html|title=When the Salsa Throbs, a Singer's Soul Is Revealed |newspaper=The New York Times |last=Scott|first=A. O.|date=August 3, 2007 |access-date=August 16, 2014}}</ref> Lopez revealed that she felt her performance in the film ''El Cantante'' should have earned her an Oscar.<ref name="CantanteOscar">{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/jennifer-lopez-deserved-oscar-nomination-role-el-cantante-article-1.198079 |title=Jennifer Lopez: I deserved an Oscar nomination for my role in 'El Cantante' |newspaper=Daily News|location=New York |last=Eisinger|first=Amy|date=January 6, 2010 |access-date=August 16, 2014}}</ref> "I feel like I had that [Oscar worthy role] in 'El Cantante,' but I don't think the academy members saw it".<ref name="CantanteOscar"/> ''El Cantante'' did not perform well at the box office, earning just $7.6 million.<ref name="BOM Breakdown" /> Lopez performed the song "Toma de Mí" for the [[El Cantante (Marc Anthony album)|film's soundtrack]]. Lopez and Anthony also launched their [[Jennifer Lopez and Marc Anthony en Concierto|co-headlining North American concert tour]] on September 28.<ref name="ld1">{{cite web|url=http://www.soundspike.com/story2/12624/jennifer-lopez-to-drop-brave-new-album/|title=Jennifer Lopez to drop 'Brave' new album|last=Kilgore|first=Kym|date=August 13, 2007|access-date=September 4, 2010|work=LiveDaily|archive-url=http://www.freezepage.com/1338238555ICJBKARMZN?url=http://www.soundspike.com/story2/12624/jennifer-lopez-to-drop-brave-new-album/ |archive-date=May 28, 2012}}</ref> Lopez's sixth studio album ''[[Brave (Jennifer Lopez album)|Brave]]'', released in October, was her lowest-charting album worldwide.<ref name="lovereview"/> The album produced two singles, "[[Do It Well]]" and "[[Hold It Don't Drop It]]". The first peaked at number 31 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart, while the latter failed to make any significant impact on the charts. A five-part [[miniseries]], ''[[Jennifer Lopez Presents: Como Ama una Mujer]]'', based on the lyrics of ''Como Ama una Mujer'' aired on [[Univision]] from October 30 to November 27, 2007. She placed her career on hiatus after giving birth to twins in February 2008.<ref name="Tampa">{{cite web|last1=Persall|first1=Steve|title=Jennifer Lopez returns from 3-year break in 'The Back-up Plan'|url=http://www.tampabay.com/features/movies/jennifer-lopez-returns-from-3-year-break-in-the-back-up-plan/1088912|website=[[Tampa Bay Times]]|access-date=December 13, 2016|date=April 21, 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510111831/http://www.tampabay.com/features/movies/jennifer-lopez-returns-from-3-year-break-in-the-back-up-plan/1088912|archive-date=May 10, 2017}}</ref> In late 2009, Lopez released two songs for her seventh studio album, ''[[Love? (album)|Love?]]'' ("[[Louboutins (song)|Louboutins]]" and "Fresh Out of the Oven"); however, the songs failed to make an appearance on the ''Billboard'' charts, which led to her departure from [[Epic Records]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/louboutins-fresh-oven-flop-epic-records-jennifer-lopez-boot-source-article-1.194874 |title=After 'Louboutins', 'Fresh Out of the Oven' flop, Epic Records gives Jennifer Lopez the boot: source |newspaper=Daily News|location=New York |author=Gatecrasher|date=February 23, 2010 |access-date=August 16, 2014}}</ref>

===2010–2013: Career rejuvenation with ''American Idol'' and ''Love?''===

Lopez parted ways with Epic Records in February 2010, citing that she had fulfilled her contractual obligations and now wished to release her seventh studio album ''[[Love?]]'' under a new label.<ref name="Billboard Lopez Leaves Sony">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/959279/updated-jennifer-lopez-confirms-split-with-epic-records |title=Updated: Jennifer Lopez Confirms Split With Epic Records |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |author1=Concepcion, Mariel |author2=Ben-Yehuda, Ayala |author3=Caulfield, Keith |date=February 23, 2010 |access-date=March 16, 2010}}</ref> Her departure from the label temporarily halted production on the album, which commenced in 2009. Upon signing a new contract with [[Island Records]], recording resumed on the album.<ref>{{cite news |author=Sarah |url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/record-producer-spills-justin-bieber-katy-perry-and-j-los-studio-secrets-2010167 |title=Record Producer Spills Justin Bieber, Katy Perry and J.Lo's Studio Secrets |work=[[Us Weekly]] |date=June 16, 2010 |access-date=October 2, 2010}}</ref> The ''[[New York Daily News]]'' revealed that Lopez would be taking some of the records recorded under Sony Music Entertainment to her new label so that they could be included on the album.<ref>{{cite news|author=Gatecrasher |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2010-02-24/gossip/27057095_1_el-cantante-sony-music-second-source |title=After 'Louboutins', 'Fresh Out of the Oven' flop, Epic Records gives Jennifer Lopez the boot |work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|location=New York |date=February 24, 2010 |access-date=May 4, 2012}}</ref> In April, Lopez starred in the romantic comedy ''[[The Back-up Plan]]'', her first theatrical role in three years.<ref name="Tampa" /> In June, following the departure of [[Ellen DeGeneres]] from ''[[American Idol]]'', it was reported that Lopez was in talks to join season ten's judging panel.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebritynews/news/source-jennifer-lopez-to-be-an-american-idol-judge-2010307 |title=Source: Jennifer Lopez to Be an American Idol Judge – Celebrity News |work=Us Weekly |access-date=August 6, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/2010/07/29/2010-07-29_ellen_degeneres_leaving_american_idol.html | newspaper=Daily News|location=New York |title=Ellen DeGeneres leaves 'American Idol'; Jennifer Lopez reportedly close to replacing her | first=Bill | last=Hutchinson | date=July 30, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2010/07/american-idols-backup-plan-with-jennifer-lopez-not-ready-for-delivery.html | work=Los Angeles Times | title=Show Tracker | date=July 30, 2010}}</ref> During this same time, Lopez and Anthony were being considered for a role on ''[[The X Factor (U.S.)|The X Factor]]'' for their appeal to Latin and International markets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/s103/the-x-factor/news/a219700/lopez-anthony-linked-to-us-x-factor.html |title=US TV – Lopez, Anthony linked to US 'X Factor' |work=[[Digital Spy]] |date=May 13, 2010 |access-date=September 18, 2010}}</ref> It was officially announced in September that Lopez would be joining the [[American Idol (season 10)|tenth season]] of ''American Idol''. MTV stated that the deal was "mutually beneficial to all those involved", while [[CNN]] reported that Lopez was viewing it as a decision to revive her career, while ''American Idol'' producers believed that Lopez and [[Steven Tyler]]'s appointments would strengthen viewing figures.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/SHOWBIZ/TV/09/22/jennifer.lopez.american.idol/ |work=CNN| title=Jennifer Lopez: A reality TV revival? | date=September 23, 2010}}</ref> In October, Lopez released her fourteenth fragrance, Love and Glamour. The perfume was inspired by Lopez's forthcoming "return to the spotlight".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.instyle.com/2010/06/07/jennifer-lopez-launches-love-and-glamour |title=Jennifer Lopez Launches Love and Glamour |work=[[InStyle]] |date=June 7, 2010 |access-date=August 8, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512044527/http://news.instyle.com/2010/06/07/jennifer-lopez-launches-love-and-glamour/ |archive-date=May 12, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

